== Planetary mass and planet formation ==
[[File:Vesta-HST-Color.jpg|thumb|[[4 Vesta|Vesta]] is the second largest body in the [[asteroid belt]] after [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]]. This image from the [[Hubble Space Telescope]] shows that it is far from being spherical.]]

The mass of a planet has consequences for its structure by having a large mass, especially while it is in the hand of [[Nebular hypothesis|process of formation]]. A body which is more than about one ten-thousandth of the mass of the Earth can overcome its [[compressive strength]] and achieve [[hydrostatic equilibrium]]: it will be roughly [[Sphere|spherical]], and since 2006 has been classified as a [[dwarf planet]] if it orbits around the Sun (that is, if it is not the [[Natural satellite|satellite]] of another planet). Smaller bodies like [[asteroid]]s are classified as "[[Small Solar System body|small Solar System bodies]]".

A dwarf planet, by definition, is not massive enough to have gravitationally [[Clearing the neighbourhood|cleared its neighbouring region]] of [[planetesimal]]s: it is not known quite how large a planet must be before it can effectively clear its neighbourhood, but one tenth of the Earth's mass is certainly sufficient.

The smaller planets retain only [[silicates]], and are [[terrestrial planet]]s like Earth or [[Mars]], though multiple-''M''<sub>E</sub> [[super-Earths]] have been discovered. The interior structure of rocky planets is mass-dependent: for example, [[plate tectonics]] may require a minimum mass to generate sufficient temperatures and pressures for it to occur.<ref>CfA Press Release Release No.: 2008-02 January 09, 2008 [http://www.cfa.harvard.edu/press/2008/pr200802.html Earth: A Borderline Planet for Life?]</ref>

If the protoplanet grows by [[accretion (astrophysics)|accretion]] to more than about {{Earth mass|5–10}}, its gravity become large enough to retain [[hydrogen]] in its [[atmosphere]]. In this case, it will grow into a [[gas giant]]. If the planet then begins [[planetary migration|migration]], it may move well within its system's [[frost line (astrophysics)|frost line]], and become a [[hot Jupiter]] orbiting very close to its star, then gradually losing small amounts of mass as the star's radiation strips its atmosphere.

The theoretical minimum mass a star can have, and still undergo hydrogen [[Nuclear fusion|fusion]] at the core, is estimated to be about {{Jupiter mass|75}}, though fusion of [[deuterium]] can occur at masses as low as 13 Jupiters.<ref>{{Citation
